Here's how to save/restore draft text using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your ContentPage (e.g., `NotePage.xaml.cs`):**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppResumed;

        // Restore any saved draft on load
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        string saved = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(saved) && string.IsNullOrEmpty(NoteEditor.Text))
        {
            NoteEditor.Text = saved;
        }
    }

    // Clear draft when user explicitly saves
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires when returning to foreground — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is lightweight key-value storage, ideal for small text. For large content, use `SecureStorage` or file I/O instead.
- Clear the draft after a successful explicit save so stale data doesn't reappear.

**Alternative:** You can also hook lifecycle events globally in `App.xaml.cs` using `CreateWindow`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { /* save state */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* restore state */ };

    return window;
}
```

Use `Resumed` (vs `Activated`) if you only want to act on return from background, not initial launch.
